Often the choice of language seems more arbitrary. A note on an execution of two criminals begins in Latin and shifts into Greek when it comes to details, as if the exotic language gives added intensity. Similarly, Hegelund drops an occasional Greek phrase at dramatic points in his otherwise Latin notes concerning war events. Drinking parties are regular- ly mentioned not in words but with a drawing of a cupâas a kind of euphemism perhaps? When Latin is no longer his normal choice, it is still used on certain solemn occasions, such as the deaths of important per- sons, or the disaster when the tower of the church collapsed during a storm. And, finally, Latin continues to be preferred for personal affairs. Notes of his official travels are in Danish, while the private trips tend to be in Latin. The same is true for comments on letter-writing and the compo- sition of books. At one point, he has had an unpleasant dream of losing some of his teethâwhich he mentions in Latin.
